<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n06053d"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n06" href="#n06053d">N06 (VI.B.11)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n06all.htm#n06053d"> 53(d)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Pigeon vole (repress imitation) / suppress words in air</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Entre autres jeux aptes &agrave; <mark>r&eacute;primer l&apos;instinct d&apos;imitation</mark> est le jeu bien connu de <mark><i>Pigeon vole</i></mark>. Enfin, comme moyen de r&eacute;sister aux habitudes prises, rien de mieux appropri&eacute; que certains exercices de langage consistant &agrave; intervertir ou &agrave; <mark>supprimer dans une lecture ou dans un chant diverses syllabes des mots</mark>. <font color="green">[Among other games apt to suppress the instinct of imitation is the well known game of Pigeon flies. Finally, as a means of resisting habits, nothing is more appropriate than certain language exercises in which words are exchanged or removed in a reading or singing of various syllables of words.]</font> <small> Fr&eacute;d&eacute;ric Queyrat, <a name="FQLJ" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#FQLJ"><cite title="source">Les Jeux des Enfants</cite></a> (1920) 110-1 footnote</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
